<blockquote>
<p>Like, the ending, the 3125 just sort of pops up.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It injects into Smith and then she tries to dethread Desai, but he eventually rallies. Then it dethreads her completely and takes her place in order to taunt Marness (at the same time that it is taunting Wheeler in Quick-Space).</p>
<blockquote>
<p>And it all seems like a big, garbled mess of just talking.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>After Cooper and Desai demanifest, it <em>is</em> just talking.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Instead of usuing actual actions</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Well none of the &quot;action&quot; is physical.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>like the common italicized text between dialogue to display what's happening,</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The italicized text is what is visible on the camera feeds, not what is happening in the noosphere.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>it seems like your trying to convey what's going on purely through dialogue and it seems odd. Does that make sense?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Well, yes. That's what I said upthread.</p>
<p>The problem is that a bunch of goofy technobabble descriptions of purely conceptual events wouldn't have made it any clearer, and don't make sense in this format. Just like a tactical shooter doesn't say, &quot;I am aiming, I am squeezing the trigger, I am double-tapping, and I am shifting my aim to the head and firing again&quot; they just do it, an identity warrior doesn't say &quot;I am entangling my threads with theirs, based first on common elements, and now I am injecting the package into their narrative, now I am ending entanglement&quot; they just do it. Besides the less of that kind of mumbo-jumbo the better, since it is sure to be total nonsense.</p>

